In [152]:
most_polluted = most_polluted2021.index.to_list()

# Create a column for coloring
world["color"] = world["name0"].apply(lambda x: "#8B0000" if x in most_polluted else "#D3D3D3")

# Plot the map
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))
world.plot(ax=ax, color = world["color"], edgecolor = "black", linewidth = 0.1)

ax.axis("off")

plt.title("10 Most Polluted Countries (Highlighted in Dark Red)", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")

plt.savefig("Most_Polluted_Countries_Map.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")

plt.show()

2.2 Create a potential gain in life expectancy (relative to the WHO guideline) map of eastern v/s western europe at GADM level 2 and save it as a high quality PDF.¶

  • Plot should be in AQLI “Potential gain in life expectancy” color scale. Visit AQLI website Index page > See legend for “Potential gain in life expectancy” and infer “exact” colors from that.
  • You can define east and west europe based on any acceptable definition online, but whatever definition you use - mention the source.
  • Feel free to add annotations/text boxes etc. to help explain the visualization.

# Plot using 'YlOrRd' colormap
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))

# Get min & max PGLE values for Eastern & Western Europe
min_llpp_who_2021 = world[world["EU_Region"].isin(["Eastern Europe", "Western Europe"])]["llpp_who_2021"].min()
max_llpp_who_2021 = world[world["EU_Region"].isin(["Eastern Europe", "Western Europe"])]["llpp_who_2021"].max()

world[world["EU_Region"] == "Eastern Europe"].plot(column="llpp_who_2021", cmap="YlOrRd", 
                                            edgecolor="black", linewidth=0.1, alpha=0.7, ax=ax, vmin=min_llpp_who_2021, vmax=max_llpp_who_2021, legend=True)

world[world["EU_Region"] == "Western Europe"].plot(column="llpp_who_2021", cmap="YlOrRd", 
                                            edgecolor="blue", linewidth=0.1, alpha=0.7, ax=ax, vmin=min_llpp_who_2021, vmax=max_llpp_who_2021,  legend=False)

ax.axis("off")
ax.set_xlim(-30, 50)  # Longitude range for Europe
ax.set_ylim(30, 75)   # Latitude range for Europe

plt.title("Potential Gain in Life Expectancy (Relative to WHO Guideline) - Eastern vs. Western Europe", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")

# Add a text box explaining the visualization
plt.annotate("Eastern Europe", xy=(25, 55), xycoords='data', fontsize=14, color="black", fontweight="bold")
plt.annotate("Western Europe", xy=(-5, 50), xycoords='data', fontsize=14, color="blue", fontweight="bold")

textstr = "• Data Source: AQLI & GADM\n• Eastern vs. Western Europe based on UN Statistics Division\n• Colors based on AQLI official scale"
plt.annotate(textstr, xy=(0.02, 0.02), xycoords="figure fraction", fontsize=10, color="black", bbox=dict(facecolor="white", alpha=0.8))

# Save as high-quality PDF
plt.savefig("Potential_Gain_Life_Expectancy_EW_Europe.pdf", dpi=600, bbox_inches="tight", format="pdf")

plt.show()

4. Verbal reasoning and writing¶

Please read the following excerpt from the AQLI Annual Update 2024 carefully and summarize your key takeaways in three clearly written bullet points. Each bullet should not exceed 30 words.

Key Takeaways from AQLI Annual Update 2024¶

  • The most polluted regions have air six times dirtier than the cleanest ones, cutting 2.7 years more from life expectancy in these areas.

  • While 94 countries (81% of the world’s population) have PM2.5 air quality standards, weak enforcement often prevents meaningful pollution reduction.

  • If all regions met their own air quality standards, the world would gain 3 billion life-years, with Iraq, Bangladesh, and Pakistan seeing nearly 2 years of added life expectancy.
